The
Corydalis species
have been reported as rich in protoberberinetype alkaloids, such as dehydrocorydaline and palmatine. Yanhusanines H-L ( 2–6 ) are oxidatively ring-opened derivatives with a unique 13,13a- seco protoberberine skeleton, which are different from the common benzylisoquinoline alkaloids. To our knowledge, only few of the alkaloids with this skeleton, such as chingazumianine (
), tomentellines C and D (
), and 6,7-methylenedioxy-2-(6-acetyl-2,3-methylenedioxybenzyl)-1(2 H )-isoquinolinone (
), have been reported as natural products. During the extract fractionation process in this study, dehydrocorydaline and palmatine were isolated from the
C. yanhusuo
tubers in large quantities. These compounds might be biosynthetic precursors for these rare 13, 13a- seco -protoberberines. The proposed biosynthetic pathway for 2–6 is shown in Fig. 5 . Dehydrocorydaline and palmatine undergo an oxidative cleavage of the C13–C13a bond to generate the putative precursors a and b , respectively, which continued to undergo nucleophilic addition to give rise to c and d , respectively. Then, a lactone ring closure via the loss of a molecule of H 2 O from c or oxidation reaction in d , generates 2 and 6, respectively. 3 is probably biosynthesized from b after reduction. 4 and 5 are presumably derived from
3 via
dehydrogenation and demethylation, respectively.

Previous reports have demonstrated that overproduction of NO in the macrophage inflammatory cascade is usually the consequence of the aberrant expression or the inhibited efficiency of iNOS (
). As expected, the LPS-induced RAW264.7 macrophage cells showed an obviously increased expression of iNOS. However, pretreatment with 4 notably attenuated theLPS induction of high expression of iNOS at concentrations of 5 and 10 μ M ( Fig. 6A ). To understand the inhibition effect of 4 on the efficiency of iNOS, the possible affinity interaction between 4 and iNOS was predicted using molecular docking studies. As shown in Fig. 6B and C , the molecular docking of 4 into the active site pocket of iNOS suggested its interactions with the residues which interacted directly with the reported inhibitors. It not only exhibited H-bond interactions between the two carbonyl units and Gln 263, but also displayed π- π interactions between the conjugated isoquinolinone moiety of 4 and the key active site residue Glu 377 of iNOS. In addition, π- π interactions were also observed between aromatic ring and Arg 388. The above results indicated that 4 may exert the inhibitory effect against NO production by dual inhibition of the expression level and efficiency of iNOS (
).

Various lines of evidence support the importance of the NF-κB pathway in the regulation of pro-inflammatory mediator production, thereby playing a key role in inflammation. The p65 component contains the main trans-activating domain responsible for NF-κB transcription factor function. Phosphorylation of IκB α (p-IκB α ) plays an important role in the process of nuclear translocation and activation of NF-κB. The IκB kinase (IκK), which is responsible for phosphorylation of IκB, is the key to NF-κB activation (
;
;
). Therefore, Western blot analyses of the expression levels of p-p65 NF-κB, p65 NF-κB, p-IκB α , IκB α , p-IκK, and IκK proteins were carried out to further disclose the mechanism of anti-inflammatory action of 4 . As shown in Fig. 8 , the expression of the phosphorylated IκB α , IκK, and p65 NF-κB was obviously increased in LPS-induced RAW264.7 cells, which indicates the activation of NF-κB signaling pathway. Whereas, pretreatment with 4 diminished the expression of p-IκB α , p-IκK, and p-p65 NF-κB. These data confirm that 4 could regulate the inflammatory response by inhibiting the NF-κB signaling pathway.
